I'm not sure if it is intentional, but I sat through three light cycles in the turn lane traveling East on Nebraska Ave trying to turn left to head North on Belcher Rd. I was taking my daughter to school and she was late because we sat at this light for 7 minutes. The turn signal does not turn to flashing yellow due to the presence of crossing guards at this intersection. Also, the duration of the light when it does turn green is a maximum of 5 seconds. Because of these issues, this turn lane becomes unnecessarily backed up. I'm sure you can understand the frustration this causes and I hope that there is a reasonable  solution to help improve this intersection. Thank you.

Can you work with the City of Tucson to find a way to get the trash out of the medians and ditches? I-10 through and east of Tucson is awful for trash. Once a year cleanings aren't enough. Mowing makes the problem worse as it spreads the trash and further reveals it. How does Phoenix keep their roads so clean? Is there equipment that could be purchased to do this? How about hiring people who are currently unemployed? I live in eastern Pima Cty and it makes me sad to travel to Tucson where I see how little we care about our environment. Most likely a lot of the trash blows out of the backs of trucks. How can this be fixed? In Canada they have roadside bins and huge fines for littering. It's so ugly; it makes it hard to see the beauty of our desert.

Please DO NOT pave or repair potholes on Palomino Road. I own homes at 5971, 5961 and 5951 South Palomino and have lived here for over 40 years. All of the stop signs and speed limit signs are broken, nobody stops and everybody speeds. It is dangerous to pull out of my driveways and at least 3 people have died on Palomino. The only thing slowing the massive traffic increase is the potholes. If you HAVE to fix the potholes for school busses, etc, Please make the repairs extremely bumpy, this will slow down the short-cutters between Ajo and Valencia. The Sheriff cannot handle the problem, I tried to get speed bumps back in 1980 but the neighbors did not want them. We are tired of vehicles crashing into our fences and gates, not to mention the VW bus upside down in my front yard. More people will die due to excessive speed and drunken driving, hopefully my family does not get creamed pulling onto Palomino. A very bumpy road would prevent the gouges in the dip and cars becoming airborne. The 25 mph speed limit is fine for a bumpy road, unfortunately, everyone goes much faster than that. Thank You for your consideration.

I've lived in Downtown Orlando in the central business district for 6 years, and in NYC for 20 other years.  I'm not averse to noise, Orlando though has become the most unregulated city for venues playing music outdoors as loud as they like, or indoor bars which put speakers on their roof or sidewalk, which are increasing by the week.  They seem to outdo each other for how loud they can play music, and talking with the Orlando Police, they report their hands are tied.  The same for vehicles with extremely loud sound systems in the beds of pick up trucks.  The police said they've been told not to bother them anymore, to let them be by the city. Venues can play as loud as they want outdoors and they really 'have no teeth'.  I get we want taxes from the drunken crowd, but success for Orlando will come with more tax generation from growing industries, and professionals gentrifying downtown.  Cities can limit the use of ANY outdoor amplification at all hours to a lowered db limit, and require a special permit and hour regulations.  Our entertainment/bar venues can play their music indoors as loud as they want.  There's no logical reason the city allows all the rooftop and outdoor venues from lately increasing the levels to such an unregulated point.

I've lived in Downtown Orlando in the central business district for 6 years, and in NYC for 20 other years.  I'm not averse to noise, Orlando though has become the most unregulated city for venues playing music outdoors as loud as they like, or indoor bars which put speakers on their roof or sidewalk, which are increasing by the week.  They seem to outdo each other for how loud they can play music, and talking with the Orlando Police, they report their hands are tied.  The same for vehicles with extremely loud sound systems in the beds of pick up trucks.  The police said they've been told not to bother them anymore, to let them be by the city. Venues can play as loud as they want outdoors and they really 'have no teeth'.  I get we want taxes from the drunken crowd, but success for Orlando will come with more tax generation from growing industries, and professionals gentrifying downtown.  Cities can limit the use of ANY outdoor amplification at all hours to a lowered db limit, and require a special permit and hour regulations.  Our entertainment/bar venues can play their music indoors as loud as they want.  There's no logical reason the city allows all the rooftop and outdoor venues from lately increasing the levels to such an unregulated point.

Central Street in recent years has increasingly become a cut through street for traffic in morning rush hour on Route 62 heading toward West Concord and Route 2. I live at 273 Central St and for the last 20 minutes dozens of cars have been doing this. It is worst between 8-9 am. This is a neighborhood of many children walking and biking to school and the high speeds of these cut through drivers is dangerous and disruptive. It would help if the Concord police would periodically be a visible presence near the Brown St/Central St intersection or on Brown near Rte 62 to deter cut through driving and ticket those who are speeding. Also it would help to put up signs prohibiting cut through traffic between 7:30 -9:30 am and posting speed limit at 20 mph. I've lived in Downtown Orlando in the central business district for 6 years, and in NYC for 20 other years.  I'm not averse to noise, Orlando though has become the most unregulated city for venues playing music outdoors as loud as they like, or indoor bars which put speakers on their roof or sidewalk, which are increasing by the week.  They seem to outdo each other for how loud they can play music, and talking with the Orlando Police, they report their hands are tied.  The same for vehicles with extremely loud sound systems in the beds of pick up trucks.  The police said they've been told not to bother them anymore, to let them be by the city. Venues can play as loud as they want outdoors and they really 'have no teeth'.  I get we want taxes from the drunken crowd, but success for Orlando will come with more tax generation from growing industries, and professionals gentrifying downtown.  Cities can limit the use of ANY outdoor amplification at all hours to a lowered db limit, and require a special permit and hour regulations.  Our entertainment/bar venues can play their music indoors as loud as they want.  There's no logical reason the city allows all the rooftop and outdoor venues from lately increasing the levels to such an unregulated point.

At 4:45 PM on 12/11/19, I was proceeding on Martling Ave after waiting at a red light at Martling/Slosson. After a few seconds, my rearview mirror was filled with the bright blue-white headlights of a truck aggressively tailgating me. I was going 25-30 mph. Suddenly the truck crossed the double yellow line into opposite traffic and pulled up alongside me. When I honked, the tow truck cut in front of me and slammed on their brakes to threaten me into an accident. After a few seconds, the truck proceeded, at 10 mph. I took a photo of the license plate when we reached the red light at Martling/Clove Rd. When we made the right turn onto Clove, the tow truck continued to travel at 10 mph on purpose. There was traffic behind me, so I honked. The truck slammed on brakes again, refusing to move for several seconds. The car behind me chose to use the bike lane/shoulder to go around us. When I tried to do the same, the truck revved its engine and wouldn't let me get past. When we reached the light at Clove/Broadway, the car that was behind me and went around was at the red light. I slowed for the red light, knowing that there's no way I would get around the tow truck without getting into a collision. The tow truck sped past the car in front, cut in front, and then turned off its lights to drive dark. It turns out the truck was also going the same direction I was, on Bard (I was far behind the truck at this point due to waiting to make the left turn on Bard) to Forest. On Forest, the tow truck driver narrowly missed hitting a pedestrian and quickly took the right turn onto Metropolitan Ave. The truck is red, and I didn't catch the name of the company that actually owns the truck so I can't complain directly to them. There is a AAA logo across the rear window as well, so I'm issuing a complaint to them as well for this driver's conduct. It was dangerous and absolutely uncalled for. I was terrified. The license plate number is 23186TT.

Thank You for your consideration.
